{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}} {{Infobox flag |Name = State of Hawaii |Article = |Image = Flag of Hawaii.svg |Alt = Flag of Hawaii |Nickname = {{lang|haw|Ka Hae Hawai{{okina}}i}} |Use = 110000 |Symbol = |Proportion =1:2 |Adoption = {{Start date and age|1845|12|29|}} |Design = Eight alternating horizontal stripes of white, red, and blue, with a Union flag in the canton |Designer = }} The current official [[flag]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Hawaii]] ([[Hawaiian language|Hawaiian]]: ''{{lang|haw|Ka Hae Hawai{{okina}}i}}'') had also previously been used by the [[Kingdom of Hawaii|kingdom]], [[Provisional Government of Hawaii|protectorate]], [[Republic of Hawaii|republic]], and [[Territory of Hawaii|territory]] of [[Hawaiian archipelago|Hawaii]]. The flag includes the flag of a foreign country, the [[Union Jack]] of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]], a remnant of the [[British Empire]]'s [[Paulet affair (1843)|influence]] on [[History of Hawaii|Hawaiian history]].
==Design== [[File:Flag-of-hawaii-flying.jpg|thumb|right|The flag of Hawaii flying in [[Haleakalā National Park]]]] The [[canton (heraldry)|canton]] of the flag of Hawaii contains the [[Union Jack|Union Flag]] of the [[United Kingdom]], prominent over the top quarter closest to the flag mast. The field of the flag is composed of eight horizontal stripes, symbolizing the eight major islands ([[Hawaii (island)|Hawai{{okina}}i]], [[Maui]], [[Kahoolawe|Kaho{{okina}}olawe]], [[Lanai|Lāna{{okina}}i]], [[Molokai|Moloka{{okina}}i]], [[Oahu|O{{okina}}ahu]], [[Kauai|Kaua{{okina}}i]], and [[Niihau|Ni{{okina}}ihau]]). Other versions of the flag have only seven stripes, probably representing the islands with the exception of Kaho{{okina}}olawe or Ni{{okina}}ihau. The color of the stripes, from the top down, follows the sequence: white, red, blue, white, red, blue, white, red. The colors were standardized in 1843, although other combinations have been seen and are occasionally still used.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hawaii.gov/hidocs/hawaiinames.html#flag |title=Name and Insignia of Hawaii – State Flag |accessdate=October 25, 2007 |date=March 1, 2006 |publisher=Hawaii State Library |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070511012617/http://www.hawaii.gov/hidocs/hawaiinames.html#flag |archivedate=May 11, 2007 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>''[[BBC History]]'', Jan 2008</ref>
In 2001, a survey conducted by the [[North American Vexillological Association]] (NAVA) placed Hawaii's flag 11th in design quality out of the 72 Canadian provincial, U.S. state and U.S. territorial flags ranked.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nava.org/digital-library/design/surveys/2001-State-Provincial-Flag-Survey.pdf|title=2001 State/Provincial Flag Survey - NAVA.org|work=nava.org}}</ref>
==Origins== [[File:Flag of the British East India Company (1801).svg|thumb|Flag of the British [[East India Company]]]] [[File:Flag of Hawaii (1816).svg|thumb|Flag of Hawaii, 1816–1845]] [[File:Flag of Hawaii (1896).svg|thumb|Flag of Hawaii in 1896]] There are various accounts of the earliest history of the flag of Hawaii. One relates how King [[Kamehameha I]] flew a British flag, probably a [[Red Ensign]], given to him by British explorer Captain [[George Vancouver]] as a token of friendship with [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]]. Subsequent visitors reported seeing the flag flying from places of honour, as it was then considered an official Hawaiian flag.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/flag-of-Hawaii|title=flag of Hawaii - United States state flag|publisher=}}</ref> As the union jack added diagonal red cross of St Patrick in 1801, so did the flag of Hawaii.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-35890670 |title=Which flags still include the union jack? |website=BBC News|date=March 24, 2016 |first=Justin |last=Parkinson}}</ref> An adviser to Kamehameha noted that the Union Flag could draw Hawaii into international conflict, as his kingdom could be seen as an ally of the United Kingdom, and he subsequently lowered the Union Flag over his home at [[Kamakahonu]]. While disputed as historically accurate, one account stated that in order to placate U.S. interests during the [[War of 1812]], a flag of the U.S. was raised over Kamehameha's home, only to be removed when British officers in the court of Kamehameha vehemently objected to it. This explains why the resulting flag of Hawaii was a deliberate hybrid of the two nations' flags.<ref name="quaife">{{cite book | last = Quaife | first = Milo | authorlink = |author2=M. J. Weig |author3=R. E. Appleman | title = The History of the United States Flag | publisher = Harper | year = 1961 | location = New York | page = 154 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=YkYJAQAAIAAJ&q }}</ref>
In 1816, Kamehameha commissioned his own flag to avoid this conflict, which has evolved into the current flag. It was probably designed by one of the commanders of the Royal Hawaiian Navy, former officers of the British [[Royal Navy]], who advised Kamehameha, based on a form of the [[British ensign|British naval flag]]. There is debate as to the actual designer: some credit [[Alexander Adams (Hawaii)|Alexander Adams]], others [[George Charles Beckley]]. It was very similar to the flag of the British [[East India Company]] in use about this time which had only red and white stripes. Captain Adams used this flag for the first time on a Hawaiian trade mission to [[China]] in 1817.<ref>{{cite book |title= From sword to share: or a fortune in five years at Hawaii |author= Henry Whalley Nicholson |pages=83–85 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=JfwrAAAAYAAJ |publisher= W.H. Allen & Co |year=1889 }}</ref>
The original flag was designed to feature stripes alternating in the order red-white-blue, also attributed to various historical flags of the United Kingdom. The flag used at the first official flying of the flag of Hawaii mistakenly placed the stripes in the order white-red-blue,<ref name="fotw.net">{{cite web|url=http://www.fotw.net/flags/us-hi_hi.html |title=Hawaii: historical flags |publisher=Fotw.net |accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref> although it seems explorers to the island disagree about the exact order of colors and the number of stripes up to the late 1840s. There may have been possibly different versions of the flag with different numbers of stripes and colors.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Reversal of the Hawaiian Flag |year=1906|publisher= |author= Howard M. Ballou | ISBN= 0-8028-5088-X |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ol7GL0CNCH4C&source=gbs_navlinks_s | pages= 5–11}}</ref> The number of stripes also changed: originally, the flag was designed with either seven or nine horizontal stripes, and in 1845 it was officially changed to eight stripes. The latter arrangement was adopted and is used today.<ref name="quaife" />
== ''Ka Hae Hawaii'' Day == In 1990, Governor of Hawaii [[John D. Waihee III|John Waihee]] proclaimed July 31 to be ''Ka Hae Hawaii'' Day, the Hawaiian [[Flag Day]]. It has been celebrated each year since then.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.aol.com/lvhalau/HawFlagProcl.html |title=Hawaiian Flag Day Proclamation |accessdate=October 26, 2007 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060703123112/http://members.aol.com/lvhalau/HawFlagProcl.html |archivedate=July 3, 2006 }}</ref> It is the same date as ''Lā Hoʻihoʻi Ea'', [[Sovereignty Restoration Day]], a holiday of the [[Kingdom of Hawaii|Kingdom of Hawaiʻi]] that is celebrated by proponents of the [[Hawaiian sovereignty movement]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Hoʻokahua Staff|title=Lā Hoʻihoʻi Ea: Hawaiʻi Commemorates Sovereignty Restoration Day|date=July 2014|work=Kaleinamanu Hawaiian Cultural Center, Kamehameha Schools|url=https://apps.ksbe.edu/kaiwakiloumoku/lahoihoiea|accessdate=September 3, 2011|ref=}}</ref>
== Flag of the Governor == {{See also|Flags of the Governors of the U.S. States}} The flag used by the [[governor of Hawaii]] is a red and blue bi-color. In the middle of the eight white stars appears the name of the state in all capital letters. During the time Hawaii was a United States territory, the letters in the middle of the flag were "TH", which stood for "Territory of Hawaii".<ref name="gov">{{cite web |url=http://www.hawaii.gov/hidocs/hawaiinames.html#governor |title=Name and Insignia of Hawaii – Governor's Flag |accessdate=October 25, 2007 |date=March 1, 2006 |publisher=Hawaii State Library |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070511012617/http://www.hawaii.gov/hidocs/hawaiinames.html#governor |archivedate=May 11, 2007 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>{{Clear}}
