{{Infobox artwork | image_file=Artemisia Gentileschi - Judith Beheading Holofernes - WGA8563.jpg | title=Judith Slaying Holofernes | artist=[[Artemisia Gentileschi]] | year=c. 1614–20 | medium=Oil on canvas | height_metric=158.8 | width_metric=125.5 | metric_unit=cm | height_imperial=(6' 6" X 5' 4") 78.33 | width_imperial=64.13 | imperial_unit=in | city=Florence | museum=[[Uffizi Gallery]] }} '''''Judith Slaying Holofernes''''' is a painting by the [[Italy|Italian]] early [[Baroque]] artist [[Artemisia Gentileschi]] completed between 1614 and 1620.<ref name="Gardner583">{{cite book | last = Gardner | first = Helen | authorlink = |author2=Fred Kleiner |author3=Christin Mamiya | title = Gardner's Art Through the Ages: A Global History 14th edition | publisher = Wadsworth | year = 2013 | location = | page = 683 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-1-111-77152-2}} </ref> The work shows the scene of [[Judith beheading Holofernes]], common in art since the early [[Renaissance]], as part of the group of subjects art critics have called the "[[Power of Women]]", which show women triumphing over powerful men. The subject takes an episode from the [[apocrypha]]l [[Book of Judith]] in the [[Old Testament]], which recounts the assassination of the [[Assyria]]n general [[Holofernes]] by the [[Israelite]] heroine [[Judith]]. The painting shows the moment when Judith, helped by her maidservant, beheads the general after he has fallen asleep drunk.
The painting is relentlessly physical, from the wide [[spurts of blood]] to the energy of the two women as they perform the act.<ref name="Gardner583" /> The effort of the women's struggle is most finely represented by the delicate face of the maid, who is younger than in most paintings, which is grasped by the oversized, muscular fist of Holofernes as he desperately struggles to survive. Although the painting depicts a classic scene from the Bible, Gentileschi drew herself as Judith and her mentor [[Agostino Tassi]], who was tried for and convicted of her rape, as Holofernes. Gentileschi's biographer Mary Garrard famously proposed an autobiographical reading of the painting, stating that it functions as "a cathartic expression of the artist's private, and perhaps repressed, rage".<ref>Mary Garrard, ''Artemisia Gentileschi'' (1989), qtd. in {{cite book | last = Phillippy | first = Patricia Berrahou | authorlink = | title = Painting women: cosmetics, canvases, and early modern culture | publisher = JHU Press | year = 2006 | location = | page = 75 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uUHueWIol9YC&pg=PA75 | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-8018-8225-8}}</ref> She also painted [[Judith Slaying Holofernes (Artemisia Gentileschi, Florence)|a later version of the work]] in the early 1620s, now in the Uffizi in Florence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/asset-viewer/judith-and-holofernes/oQF3gDEYNkutBA?projectId=art-project&hl=en|title=Judith and Holofernes|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Art Project|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khanacademy.org/humanities/monarchy-enlightenment/baroque-art1/baroque-italy/a/gentileschi-judith-slaying-holofernes|title=Gentileschi, Judith Slaying Holofernes|last=Camara|first=Esperança|date=|website=Khan Academy|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>
==Related works== Gentileschi's self-insertion was reversed in an influential composition by [[Cristofano Allori]] (c. 1613 onwards), which exists in several versions and copied a conceit of Caravaggio's recent ''[[David with the Head of Goliath (Caravaggio, Rome)|David with the Head of Goliath]]''; here the head is a portrait of the artist, Judith his ex-mistress, and the maid her mother.<ref>Lucy Whitaker, Martin Clayton, ''The Art of Italy in the Royal Collection; Renaissance and Baroque'', p. 270, Royal Collection Publications, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-902163-29-1}}</ref>
Gentileschi painted another painting, ''[[:File:Gentileschi judith1.jpg|Judith and her Maidservant]]'' (1613–14), which shows Judith holding a dagger while her maidservant carries a basket containing a severed head. ''[[:File:Gentileschi judith1.jpg|Judith and her Maidservant]]'' is displayed in the Palazzo Pitti, in Florence. A further three paintings by Gentileschi, in Naples, Detroit and Cannes, show her maid covering the head of Holofernes, while Judith herself looks out the frame of the picture.
[[Judith beheading Holofernes]] has been depicted by a number of artists including [[Giorgione]], [[Titian]], [[Rembrandt]], [[Peter Paul Rubens]] and [[Caravaggio]].
[[File:Judith Beheading Holofernes by Caravaggio.jpg|left|thumb|[[Caravaggio]], ''[[Judith Beheading Holofernes (Caravaggio)|Judith Beheading Holofernes]],'' c. 1598–1599. In Caravaggio's version the beheading seems effortless, in stark contrast to Gentileschi's depictions]] [[Caravaggio]]'s ''[[Judith Beheading Holofernes (Caravaggio)|Judith Beheading Holofernes]]'' is believed to be the main source of this work, and his influence shows in the naturalism and violence Gentileschi brings to her canvas. In both there is a notable absence of decorative detail in the background.<ref name="WGOA">"[http://www.wga.hu/frames-e.html?/html/g/gentiles/artemisi/judit.html Judith Beheading Holofernes]". [[Web Gallery of Art]]. Retrieved on June 6, 2009.</ref> Gentileschi's father, [[Orazio Gentileschi]], was also a famous painter; he was also very much influenced by Caravaggio's style and painted his own version of the tale, ''[[:File:Orazio Gentileschi - Judith and Her Maidservant with the Head of Holofernes.JPG|Judith and Her Maidservant with the Head of Holofernes]]''.
