{{Infobox building | name = Mammy's Cupboard | image = Mammy's Cupboard Restaurant, Natchez, Mississippi, by Carol M. Highsmith.jpg | image_alt = | caption = | map_type = | map_alt = | map_caption = | altitude = | building_type = Restaurant | architectural_style = [[Novelty architecture]] | structural_system = | cost = | address = 555 U.S. 61 | location_town = near [[Natchez, Mississippi]] | location_country = [[United States]] | coordinates = {{coord|31|28|41|N|91|22|17|W|display=inline,title}} | groundbreaking_date = | opened_date = {{start date|1940}} | height = {{convert|28|ft|abbr=on}} | roof = | other_dimensions = | main_contractor = | architect = | other_designers = | quantity_surveyor = | awards = | designations = | url = | embedded = | references = }} '''Mammy's Cupboard''' (founded 1940)<ref name="Roadside"/> is a roadside restaurant built in the shape of a [[mammy archetype]],<ref name="Roadside">{{cite book |title=Roadside Giants |last=Butko |first=Brian |author2=Butko, Sarah |year=2005 |publisher=Stackpole Books |isbn=978-0-8117-3228-4 |page=7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hA1raIgFcAQC&pg=PA7&dq=mammy%27s+cupboard&hl=en&ei=id5sToiQKuGCsgKLud3kBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CEQQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=mammy%27s%20cupboard&f=false}}</ref> located on [[U.S. Route 61|US Highway 61]] south of [[Natchez, Mississippi]]. The woman's skirt holds a dining room and a gift shop.<ref name="Road">{{cite book |title=Road Trip USA |last=Jensen |first=Jamie |year=2009 |publisher=Avalon Travel |isbn=978-1-59880-101-9 |page=281}}</ref> The skirt is made out of [[brick]]s, and the earrings are [[horseshoes]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Big Book of Car Culture |last=Hinckley |first=Jim |author2=Robinson, Jon G. |year=2005 |publisher=MotorBooks International |isbn=978-0-7603-1965-9 |page=15 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fJ_qWhCZm04C&pg=PA15&dq=mammy%27s+cupboard&hl=en&ei=id5sToiQKuGCsgKLud3kBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CD4Q6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=mammy%27s%20cupboard&f=false}}</ref> She is holding a serving tray while smiling.<ref>{{cite book |title=Mississippi, off the beaten path |last=Carter Kirkpatrick |first=Marlo |year=2007 |publisher=Globe Pequot |isbn=978-0-7627-4422-0 |page=164 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ftJm0hwGAGEC&pg=PA164&dq=mammy%27s+cupboard&hl=en&ei=SuxsTtO-D5PisQKtt_y9BA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=mammy%27s%20cupboard&f=false}}</ref> Mammy's Cupboard has been through several renovations, the exterior has been repaired and the interior refurbished.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/3344 |title=Mammy's Cupboard |work=Roadside America}}</ref> The restaurant currently serves lunches and desserts.<ref name="Road"/>
The restaurant's founder was originally a tour guide of Natchez's nearby [[antebellum architecture|antebellum]] mansions and she believed tourists would also be interested in this type of restaurant.<ref name="Roadside"/> Also a mammy character had been portrayed in the very popular 1939 film ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'', about the same time plans for the restaurant were being made.<ref name="Roadside"/> During the [[American Civil Rights Movement|Civil Rights Movement]] of the 1960s the Mammy's skin was repainted a lighter shade.<ref name="Roadside"/> The current owner said of the Mammy, "There is honor in everything you do and for those who have young people. You have a crying child. Who are they going to run to? Nine times out of ten, they are going to run to the mammy... I want people to look at her and see that."<ref>{{cite book |title=The grace of silence |last=Norris |first=Michele |year=2010 |publisher=Random House Digital |isbn=978-0-307-37876-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3pW5AjCHRzcC&pg=PT39&dq=mammy%27s+cupboard&hl=en&ei=4uJsTq-7N8KtsQKIgPHoBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC0Q6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=mammy%27s%20cupboard&f=false}}</ref>
The author of ''Crossings: A White Man's Journey Into Black America'' described the restaurant as "a massive statue&mdash;twenty-eight feet [8.5 m] high&mdash;of a black woman dressed like [[Aunt Jemima]], wearing a red scarf, a white blouse, and a red hoopskirt that actually houses a restaurant",<ref>{{cite book |title=Crossings: a white man's journey into Black America |last=Harrington |first=Walt |year=1999 |publisher=University of Missouri Press |isbn=978-0-8262-1259-7 |page=124 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RoWIyPvjLrwC&pg=PA124&dq=mammy%27s+cupboard&hl=en&ei=id5sToiQKuGCsgKLud3kBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CEoQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=mammy%27s%20cupboard&f=false}}</ref> while the authors of ''Frommer's USA'' said that if you want to visit the restaurant, "you need to check your political correctness at the door".<ref>{{cite book |title=Frommer's USA |last=Warnock |first=Kathleen |author2=Kraus, Naomi |year=2009 |publisher=Frommer's |isbn=978-0-470-38746-7 |page=435 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cEMImk1MFM0C&pg=PA435&dq=mammy%27s+cupboard+political+correctness&hl=en&ei=mvJsTobCJbSPsALquIzVBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=mammy%27s%20cupboard%20political%20correctness&f=false}}</ref> The restaurant's homemade pie was covered in the book ''American Pie''<ref>{{cite book |title=American Pie: Slices of Life (and Pie) from America's Back Roads |last=Le Draoulec |first=Pascale |year=2003 |publisher=HarperCollins |isbn=978-0-06-095732-2 |pages=82–84 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xbvN1zlFDu0C&pg=PA82&dq=mammy%27s+cupboard+pie&hl=en&ei=MO9sTo7LHu2FsgLzudS2CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=mammy%27s%20cupboard%20pie&f=false}}</ref> and the newspaper ''[[The Press Democrat]]'' for [[National Pie Day]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pressdemocrat.com/article/20090121/LIFESTYLE/901210305?Title=Rejoice__It_s_National_Pie_Day |title=Rejoice! It's National Pie Day |author=Michele Anna Jordon |date=January 21, 2009 |work=[[The Press Democrat]]}}</ref>
